Enjoying chamber music -- tVisit to places associated with musicians: England and music -- t7. Sport -- tRowing -- tTennis and Squash -- tJogging, climbing, skiing and other sporting activities -- t8. Life as a Research Student at Oxford -- tWhy I decided to do research on the Thames as a highway -- tProfessor Mathias -- tVisiting record offices -- tDr Highfield -- tPreparing my thesis -- tCanals past and future -- t9. Travels in Britain and Abroad -- tWeekend drives in the countryside around Oxford -- tTrips in Britain involving overnight stays -- tTravelling round Europe and meeting European royal families -- t10. Looking Back on My Two Years’ Stay -- tThe English people as I saw them -- tOn Leaving Britain -- tPostscript -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPrior to becoming Crown Prince of Japan in 1989, following the death of his grandfather Emperor Showa, Prince Naruhito studied at Merton College, Oxford, from June 1983 to October 1985. His research topic was the River Thames as a commercial highway in the eighteenth century. This marked the first time that anyone in direct succession to the throne had ever studied outside Japan. In 1992, he published a record of his time at Oxford under the title Thames no tomo ni . The memoir, which includes a colour plate section incorporating photographs taken by the Prince, explores his daily life, studies and recreational experiences, including discovering beer and being banned from entering a disco because he was wearing jeans. The Thames and I is a remarkable record, not least because of its candour, but equally because it reveals the Crown Prince as an individual, including his personal charm and sense of humour. It will be of special interest to those wishing to know more about the future emperor of Japan.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on onli